On 27 February, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported that the vice president for women and the family, COVID-19, had tested positive; earlier that day, mojtaba Zonnour, chairman of the Islamic parliament's National Security and Foreign Policy Committee, released a video saying he had tested positive for the new coronavirus and was being treated under isolation. He was preceded by Iraj Harirchi, Iran's deputy health minister, and Mahmoud Sadeqi, a member of parliament who represents Tehran. The 13th District Chief of Tehran, the capital, was also diagnosed and discharged after his condition improved.

So far, Iran has confirmed 245 new cases of pneumonia, including 26 deaths, covering 20 provinces, mostly in Qom. Iran also continues to have the world's highest mortality rate of about 10.6 per 100,000 confirmed cases.

But Iran's health minister, Kianoush Jahanpour, reported that 38 of the 106 new cases confirmed that day came from Tehran, more than Qom, who had seven new cases.

Iran's supreme leader, Ali Khamenei, praised Health Minister Saeed Namaki and all medical staff Tuesday, saying their efforts for the country are "priceless" and will be blessed by God.

Iranian leaders have repeatedly dismissed the outbreak as a hostile plot against the regime. President Rohani said again on the 26th that foreign propaganda agencies used the Iranian side to cancel public activities and other preventive measures to try to manipulate public opinion to cause panic and advise the public to ignore rumors. Rohani also took aim at the United States, saying it had repeatedly tried to hamper production and economic activity in Iran to the detriment of its citizens. Ali Khamenei has previously attributed the low turnout in parliamentary elections to the influence of hostile public opinion.

Iranian police have arrested 24 people for spreading rumors on the Internet, and 118 people have been interviewed, AFP reported.

Rohani also said he had received work reports showing that Iran continues to import new coronavirus test kits from the World Health Organization (WHO) , while domestic experts have mastered the production technology of test kits and domestic products have entered the testing phase, it's GONNA go into mass production soon.

Jahanpur said 15 new coronaviruses were expected to be established in the country, bringing the total to 22 by next week.

The Ministry of Defence has also joined the production of face masks and disinfectants and set up production lines at affiliated institutions, according to Iran's english-language News television. Defence Minister Amir Hatami had ordered the department to produce 20,000 masks and 20,000 litres of disinfectant a day.

The price of anti-epidemic supplies in Iran has risen tenfold due to tight supplies, the BBC reported, with long lines at the doors of many pharmacies either buying up or selling out.

Iran's outbreak has also spread to a number of neighboring countries. A total of 43 cases, including 17 confirmed cases, were reported in Kuwait on the 27th, all related to the first passenger who had travelled to Iran. Confirmed cases linked to Iran have been reported in Iraq, Bahrain, Oman, Afghanistan, Lebanon, the United Arab Emirates, Pakistan and even Canada.

The WHO will send a team of experts to Iran this weekend to assess the situation and provide assistance.
